frameDefinitions: A Traveller leaves from or dismounts a Vehicle.

A Theme changes location with respect to a salient location, which can be expressed by a Source, Path, Goal, Area, Direction, Path_shape, or Distance, as shown in the examples below: ''  'Start your ascent from Achintree Farm in Glen Nevis.'
The words in this frame describe situations in which a Perpetrator forcibly seizes control over a Victim's Vehicle to gain some end.  ''
An Agent matches location with an Entity in order to fulfill some  Purpose.
In this frame an Emission emanates from a Source along a Path or to a Goal.
A Traveller boards a Vehicle that they intend to use as a means of transportation either as a passenger or as a driver.
frameExamples: Start your <t>ascent</t> from Achintree Farm in Glen Nevis.
French farmers have <t>hijacked</t> a lorry and destroyed its load of strawberries.
I ca n't remember how many times he <t>visited</t> ! DNI
On the 5th of December, 1834, we <t>embarked</t> on board the merchant ship Hellespont.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Traveller</fen> is the entity which disembarks from the <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
The <fen>Vehicle</fen> is the means of conveyance that the <fen>Traveller</fen> disembarks from.
When the disembarking of the <fen>Vehicle</fen> takes place.
The location in which the <fen>Traveller</fen> disembarks from the <fen>Vehicle</fen>.

This is the object which moves. In many sentences this role will be expressed as something which moves under its own power. However, this role is not <ment>required</ment> to be an animate mover, so it is different from Self_mover.

Any expression which implies a definite starting-point of motion expresses the frame element <fen>Source</fen>. In prepositional phrases, the prepositional object expresses the starting point of motion. In particles, the starting point of motion is understood from context.
Any description of a trajectory of motion which is neither a <fen>Source</fen> nor a <fen>Goal</fen> (see below) expresses the frame element <fen>Path</fen>, including directional expressions:
Any expression which tells where the <fen>Theme</fen> ends up as a result of the motion expresses the frame element Goal.
Any expression which characterizes the extent of motion expresses the frame element <fen>Distance</fen>.
This frame element is used for expressions which describe a general area in which motion takes place when the motion is understood to be irregular and not to consist of a single linear path.
The configuration formed by the entire <fen>Path</fen> of the <fen>Theme</fen>, taken simultaneously.
The direction in which the <fen>Theme</fen> goes.
The time at which the motion takes place.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the motion (which is specified by a <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen>) is located.
This is the person (or other agent) who forcibly seizes control over a vehicle to gain some end.
This is the means of transportation which gets under the control of the perpetrator. Example: The terrorists hijacked <fex name='Vehicle'>the plane</fex>.
This role describes the people that are suffering as a result of the <fen>Perpetrator</fen>'s action.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
The sentient entity that is temporarily with the <fen>Entity</fen> in order to fulfil some <fen>Purpose</fen>.

The physical entity that is permanently associated with entities or characteristics that the <fen>Agent</fen> wishes to use for some <fen>Purpose</fen>.  During the visit, the <fen>Agent</fen> matches location with the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The time at which a visit is made.
A description of the position of the <fen>Agent</fen> during the visit.
The <fen>Emission</fen>s are discharged out of the <fen>Source</fen> .
The <fen>Source</fen> is the location from which the <fen>Emission</fen> emanates.
This role identifies the time when the emanation occurs.
The <fen>Traveller</fen> is the entity which boards the <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
The <fen>Vehicle</fen> is the intended means of conveyance of the <fen>Traveller</fen>.
When the boarding of the <fen>Vehicle</fen> takes place.
The location in which the <fen>Traveller</fen> boards the <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>We</fex> got off at the wrong bus stop.
The victim stopped the tractor and dismounted <fex>from it</fex>.
<fex>Yesterday</fex>, we alighted onto this tiny hilly island, site of a Singaporean October festival.
The cat crossed the street <fex>from her yard</fex>.
The children hopped <fex>into the neighbor's yard</fex>.
I leaped <fex>twenty feet</fex> before slipping and falling.
The frogs jumped <fex>down</fex> through the meadow.
The rebels skyjacked a plane <fex>with 89 passangers</fex>.
At approximately 07:30 hours <fex>we</fex> emplaned in England and after circling to gather other units that made up the 1st Airborne Army, we headed for the Rhine.
When he had mounted <fex>the horse</fex>, his armour glittered in the sun, and he looked so brave and handsome.
Therese entrained <fex>at 9am on 4 October</fex> for the Brandhoek area. .
You can get on the shuttle bus <fex>at the Bank of America across from the BART station</fex>.
